Examples
	• Flower Species Classification 
	• Handwritten Digit Recognition 
	• Animal Classification 
	• Face Recognition 

3. Working of LDA
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
Prepare a labeled dataset with input features and corresponding class labels.
Example:
Height	Weight	Class
160	55	Class A
170	70	Class B
180	85	Class C

Step 2: Calculate the Mean of Each Class
The algorithm computes the average value for each feature within every class.
Example:
Mean of Class A = 162
Mean of Class B = 171
Mean of Class C = 181

Step 3: Compute the Within-Class Scatter Matrix
The Within-Class Scatter Matrix (SW) measures how much the data points vary within each class.
A smaller within-class scatter indicates that samples belonging to the same class are closely grouped together.

Step 4: Compute the Between-Class Scatter Matrix
The Between-Class Scatter Matrix (SB) measures how far apart the class means are from one another.
A larger between-class scatter indicates better separation between different classes.

Step 5: Find the Optimal Discriminant
LDA determines the linear combination of features that:
	• Maximizes the between-class scatter. 
	• Minimizes the within-class scatter. 
This produces the best separation between classes.

Step 6: Project the Data
The original high-dimensional data is projected into a lower-dimensional space using the computed discriminant vectors.

Step 7: Classify New Data
The transformed data is used to classify new observations into the appropriate class.

Mathematical Formula
The objective of LDA is to maximize:

J(w)=S_B/S_W 
 
Where:
	• SB = Between-Class Scatter Matrix 
	• SW = Within-Class Scatter Matrix 
	• J(w) = Objective function 
The larger the value of J(w), the better the separation between classes.

Example
Suppose a hospital wants to classify patients into:
	• Healthy 
	• Diabetes 
	• Heart Disease 
Input Features:
	• Age 
	• Blood Pressure 
	• Cholesterol 
LDA analyzes the data, finds the optimal discriminant directions, and projects the patient information into a lower-dimensional space.
Prediction:
Patient = Diabetes

Advantages
	• Simple and easy to implement. 
	• Reduces the number of features (dimensionality reduction). 
	• Improves classification accuracy when class assumptions are satisfied. 
	• Computationally efficient. 
	• Reduces overfitting by eliminating redundant features. 
	• Works well for multiclass classification. 

Disadvantages
	• Assumes data follows a normal (Gaussian) distribution. 
	• Assumes all classes have equal covariance matrices. 
	• Sensitive to outliers. 
	• Performance decreases if assumptions are violated. 
	• Not suitable for highly nonlinear datasets. 

